   "source": [
    "# Data Visualization | NYC Airbnb Dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "Going deeper than EDA plots: multi-variable visualizations, geographic plots,\n",
    "polished publication-quality charts, and knowing when to use which chart type."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "4b15b678",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "(48868, 16)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "\n",
    "df = pd.read_csv('../data/AB_NYC_2019.csv')\n",
    "df['reviews_per_month'] = df['reviews_per_month'].fillna(0)\n",
    "df = df.dropna(subset = ['name'])\n",
    "df = df[df['price'] > 0]\n",
    "\n",
    "#setting a clean visual style for all plots in the notebook\n",
    "sns.set_theme(style=\"whitegrid\", palette=\"muted\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(df.shape)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ede4e114",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Multi Variatble Bar Chart | Avg Price per Borough and Room Type\n",
    "*When to use: comparing a numeric metric across two categorical dimensions*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "5e8c6479",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# pivoting data to get the average price per neighbourhood group\n",
    "pivoted_data = df.groupby(['neighbourhood_group','room_type'])['price'].mean().reset_index()\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))\n",
    "sns.barplot(x='neighbourhood_group', y='price', hue='room_type', data=pivoted_data)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.title('Average Price per Neighbourhood Group and Room Type')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Neighbourhood Group',fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Average Price $',fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.legend(title='Room Type', loc='upper left', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1))\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ea991b79",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Insight\n",
    "- Manhattan entire home/apt listings average ~$250/night, nearly double Brooklyn's \n",
    "  (~$178) and almost triple the Bronx (~$127), reflecting NYC's real estate premium.\n",
    "- Across every borough, the room type hierarchy is consistent: \n",
    "  Entire home/apt > Private room > Shared room, with no exceptions.\n",
    "- The gap between room types is widest in Manhattan ($250 vs $117 vs $88), \n",
    "  suggesting it attracts higher-end entire home renters disproportionately.\n",
    "- Shared rooms show the least price variance across boroughs ($51 to $88), \n",
    "  suggesting a price floor effect where shared spaces can only get so cheap \n",
    "  before they are not worth listing."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ec6b6b55",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Geographic Scatter Plot | Listings Across NYC\n",
    "*When to use: any data with latitude/longitude | spatial patterns invisible in tables*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "0f9ad723",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x1000 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Sample 25,000 points for readability (plotting all 49k is slow and noisy)\n",
    "sample = df.sample(25000, random_state=42)\n",
    "\n",
    "scatter = plt.scatter(\n",
    "    sample['longitude'], \n",
    "    sample['latitude'],\n",
    "    c=sample['price'].clip(upper=500),  # cap color scale at $500\n",
    "    cmap='YlOrRd',                       # yellow=cheap, red=expensive\n",
    "    alpha=0.4,\n",
    "    s=5                                  # small dot size\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.colorbar(scatter, label='Price ($)')\n",
    "plt.title('NYC Airbnb Listings | Geographic Price Distribution', \n",
    "          fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Longitude')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Latitude')\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "05dcfe02",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Insight\n",
    "- The dense vertical strip of orange and red dots around longitude -74.0 to -73.95 \n",
    "  and latitude 40.7 to 40.85 is Manhattan, confirming it as both the most \n",
    "  listed and most expensive borough geographically.\n",
    "- The large spread of yellow dots to the right (longitude -73.9 to -73.8) is \n",
    "  Brooklyn and Queens, noticeably cheaper on average with far fewer high-price \n",
    "  listings visible.\n",
    "- The isolated cluster at the bottom left (around -74.1 to -74.2) is Staten Island, \n",
    "  sparse listings and mostly yellow, consistent with its low average prices.\n",
    "- High-price listings (red/pink dots) are not randomly scattered, they cluster \n",
    "  tightly in lower and midtown Manhattan, suggesting location within a borough \n",
    "  matters as much as the borough itself.\n",
    "- Geographic scatter plots reveal spatial concentration patterns that borough-level \n",
    "  bar charts completely hide, a neighbourhood-level analysis would likely show \n",
    "  even sharper price gradients within Manhattan itself."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a510c59b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. Violin Plot | Price Distribution by Borough\n",
    "*When to use: shows full distribution shape, not just summary stats like a boxplot*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "b0c1291d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1300x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(13, 6))\n",
    "\n",
    "sns.violinplot(data=df[df['price'] < 500],\n",
    "               x='neighbourhood_group',\n",
    "               y='price',\n",
    "               hue='neighbourhood_group',  \n",
    "               palette='muted',\n",
    "               legend=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.title('Price Distribution by Borough (Violin Plot)', \n",
    "          fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Borough', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Price ($)', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "40fd7d78",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Insight\n",
    "- Manhattan has the widest violin with mass stretching toward $500, confirming \n",
    "  a broader price range, not just a higher median.\n",
    "- Queens and the Bronx are narrowest, most listings cluster in a tight low \n",
    "  price band with very few high-end outliers.\n",
    "- Staten Island's wide base tapering sharply explains the bar chart anomaly \n",
    "  earlier, a few expensive listings pulling the average up.\n",
    "- Manhattan's IQR bar is visibly longer than other boroughs, confirming wider \n",
    "  spread around the center, not just a higher midpoint."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "48c32414",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Heatmap | Listing Density by Borough and Room Type\n",
    "*When to use: showing concentration/frequency across two categorical dimensions*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "0fe3e718",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x500 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "density = df.groupby(['neighbourhood_group', \n",
    "                       'room_type']).size().unstack(fill_value=0)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))\n",
    "sns.heatmap(density, \n",
    "            annot=True, \n",
    "            fmt='d',          # integer format\n",
    "            cmap='Blues',\n",
    "            linewidths=0.5)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.title('Listing Count by Borough and Room Type', \n",
    "          fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5b4ee450",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Insight\n",
    "- Manhattan dominates entire home/apt listings (13,192), while Brooklyn leads \n",
    "  private rooms (10,121), reflecting different hosting cultures in each borough.\n",
    "- Shared rooms are rare everywhere, no borough crosses 500, suggesting \n",
    "  guests strongly prefer private spaces.\n",
    "- Staten Island and the Bronx are thinly listed across all room types, \n",
    "  confirming they are marginal Airbnb markets compared to Manhattan and Brooklyn.\n",
    "- The darkest cell (Manhattan entire home/apt) and lightest cells (Staten Island) \n",
    "  tell the full supply story at a glance, something raw numbers in a table would \n",
    "  not convey as quickly."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2a32052b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. Polished Multi-Panel Figure\n",
    "*When to use: summarizing multiple related insights in one publication-quality figure*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "985f942f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1600x1200 with 4 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(16, 12))\n",
    "fig.suptitle('NYC Airbnb | Key Insights Dashboard', \n",
    "             fontsize=16, fontweight='bold', y=1.02)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Panel 1: Reviews vs Price\n",
    "axes[0, 0].scatter(df[df['price'] < 500]['number_of_reviews'],\n",
    "                   df[df['price'] < 500]['price'],\n",
    "                   alpha=0.2, s=5, color='steelblue')\n",
    "axes[0, 0].set_title('Reviews vs Price')\n",
    "axes[0, 0].set_xlabel('Number of Reviews')\n",
    "axes[0, 0].set_ylabel('Price ($)')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Panel 2: Room type share (pie chart)\n",
    "room_counts = df['room_type'].value_counts()\n",
    "axes[0, 1].pie(room_counts, labels=room_counts.index, \n",
    "               autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90,\n",
    "               colors=sns.color_palette('muted'))\n",
    "axes[0, 1].set_title('Room Type Distribution')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Panel 3: Top 10 neighbourhoods by listing count\n",
    "top_neighbourhoods = df['neighbourhood'].value_counts().head(10)\n",
    "axes[1, 0].barh(top_neighbourhoods.index, top_neighbourhoods.values,\n",
    "                color='steelblue')\n",
    "axes[1, 0].set_title('Top 10 Neighbourhoods by Listing Count')\n",
    "axes[1, 0].set_xlabel('Number of Listings')\n",
    "axes[1, 0].invert_yaxis()  # most popular at top\n",
    "\n",
    "# Panel 4: Availability distribution\n",
    "axes[1, 1].hist(df['availability_365'], bins=50, \n",
    "                color='steelblue', edgecolor='white')\n",
    "axes[1, 1].set_title('Availability Distribution (Days/Year)')\n",
    "axes[1, 1].set_xlabel('Days Available')\n",
    "axes[1, 1].set_ylabel('Count')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "febe532e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Insight\n",
    "- Reviews vs Price: most highly-reviewed listings are cheap, expensive listings \n",
    "  accumulate far fewer reviews, likely because they are booked less frequently.\n",
    "- Room type split is almost even: entire home/apt (52%) vs private room (45.7%), \n",
    "  shared rooms barely register at 2.4%.\n",
    "- Top neighbourhoods are dominated by Brooklyn (Williamsburg, Bedford-Stuyvesant, \n",
    "  Bushwick, Crown Heights), despite Manhattan having more total listings, \n",
    "  suggesting Brooklyn's supply is concentrated in a few dense hotspots.\n",
    "- Availability distribution shows two spikes: one near 0 days (hosts who rarely \n",
    "  make their space available) and one near 365 days (professional full-time hosts), \n",
    "  with relatively few listings in between, suggesting hosting is polarised between \n",
    "  casual and professional."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bab39f50",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Summary / Chart Type Reference\n",
    "\n",
    "| Chart type | When to use |\n",
    "|---|---|\n",
    "| Bar chart | Comparing a numeric metric across categories |\n",
    "| Grouped bar | Comparing across two categorical dimensions |\n",
    "| Scatter plot | Relationship between two continuous variables |\n",
    "| Geographic scatter | Any data with lat/long  spatial patterns |\n",
    "| Violin plot | Full distribution shape across categories (richer than boxplot) |\n",
    "| Heatmap | Frequency/concentration across two categorical dimensions |\n",
    "| Pie chart | Part-to-whole composition (use sparingly | bar charts are usually clearer) |\n",
    "| Multi-panel | Summarizing multiple insights in one figure |\n",
    "\n",
    "**Key takeaway**: choosing the wrong chart type obscures rather than reveals \n",
    "insight. Match the chart to what you're trying to show, not what looks impressive.\n",
    "\n",
   ]
  }
